<section>
  <title>Executive summary: l'H&#xf4;pital's rule</title>
  <introduction>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Definitions</title>
    <theorem>
      <title>Indeterminate forms</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a limit expression of the form
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}
          </me>,
          where <m>a</m> is either a finite number or <m>\pm\infty</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The expression is an <em>indeterminate form of type <m>0/0</m></em> if
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=0
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The expression is an <em>indeterminate form of type <m>\infty/\infty</m></em> if
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\pm\infty \text{ and }  \lim_{x\to a}g(x)=\pm\infty
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <theorem>
      <title>Further indeterminate forms</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Assume <m>a</m> is either a finite number or <m>\pm\infty</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=\infty</m>,
          then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)-g(x)</m> is an
          <em>indeterminate form of type <m>\infty-\infty</m></em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=0</m> and <m>\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=\pm\infty</m>,
          then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)g(x)</m> is an <em></em>indeterminate
        </p>
        <p>
          form of type <m>0\cdot\infty</m>}.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=0</m>,
          then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)^{g(x)}</m> is an
          <em>indeterminate form of type <m>0^0</m></em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\infty</m> and <m>\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=0</m>,
          then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)^{g(x)}</m> is an
          <em>indeterminate form of type <m>\infty^0</m></em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=1</m> and <m>\lim_{x\to a}g(x)=\infty</m>,
          then <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}f(x)^{g(x)}</m> is an
          <em>indeterminate form of type <m>1^\infty</m></em>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Theory</title>
    <theorem>
      <title>L'H&#xf4;pital's rule</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be differentiable on an open interval <m>I</m> containing <m>a</m>,
          where <m>a</m> is either a finite number or <m>\pm\infty</m>,
          and suppose <m>g'(x)\ne 0</m> for all <m>x\ne a</m> in the interval.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}</m> is an indeterminate form of type <m>0/0</m> or <m>\infty/\infty</m>, then
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}=\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f'(x)}{g'(x)}
          </me>,
          provided the limit on the right exists or is equal to <m>\pm\infty</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The same result holds if we replace the limit with a one-sided limit.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Examples</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Decide whether the following limit expressions have determinate or indeterminate forms.
          If determinate, compute the limit.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0+}\frac{\sin x}{\ln x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to (\pi/2)^-}\frac{\tan x}{\cos x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to\infty}\frac{e^x}{2^x+3^x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute the following limits.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to\infty}\frac{\ln x}{x^{1000}}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{2^x-3^{-x}}{4^x-5^{-x}}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\frac{\cos(\pi x/2)}{\log_2(x)}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\frac{x-\sin x}{x\sin x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute the following limits.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^+}\frac{1}{\sin x}-\frac{1}{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to \infty}2x-\sqrt{4x^2-13x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -\infty}x^22^{x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^+}(1+x)^{1/x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to \infty}(1+x^2)^{2/x}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
</section>